  "text": "Private expenditure on health care includes out-of-pocket (OOP) spending and also expenditure by insurers ('pre-paid plans'). The WHO health expenditure database 8 has reasonably comparable crosscountry data despite conceptual and measurement problems [CITATION_1] . The extent of each type of private finance is a proxy indicator of the characteristics of the private supply sector, since private insurance generally funds larger licensed private providers, while much OOP spending funds smaller scale, often unlicensed provision.",
